{
  "How many basic tissue types are recognized in the human body?": "",
  "4": "",
  "2": "",
  "3": "",
  "6": "",
  "The four primary tissue types are epithelial, connective, muscle, and nervous tissue, and every organ in the body is composed of varying combinations of these four types.": "",
  "The most abundant and diverse tissue type in the body is:": "",
  "Nervous tissue": "",
  "Epithelial tissue": "",
  "Muscle tissue": "",
  "Connective tissue": "",
  "Connective tissue is the most widespread and varied tissue type in the body, encompassing bone, blood, cartilage, adipose (fat), and various types of fibrous connective tissue.": "",
  "Blood is classified as which type of tissue?": "",
  "Blood is classified as a connective tissue because it consists of cells (red blood cells, white blood cells, platelets) suspended in a liquid extracellular matrix called plasma.": "",
  "Skeletal muscle is characterized as:": "",
  "Involuntary and striated": "",
  "Voluntary and non-striated": "",
  "Voluntary and striated": "",
  "Involuntary and smooth": "",
  "Skeletal muscle is under voluntary (conscious) control and displays striations (visible cross-stripes) due to the highly organized arrangement of actin and myosin filaments within the sarcomeres.": "",
  "Cardiac muscle is found exclusively in the:": "",
  "Intestines": "",
  "Blood vessels": "",
  "Biceps": "",
  "Heart": "",
  "Cardiac muscle tissue is found only in the wall of the heart (myocardium), where it contracts involuntarily and rhythmically to pump blood throughout the body.": "",
  "Smooth muscle is found in the walls of:": "",
  "Skeletal muscles that attach to bones throughout the limbs and trunk": "",
  "The outer layer of the skin and the lining of the nasal cavity": "",
  "Hollow organs such as the stomach, blood vessels, and bladder": "",
  "Tendons and ligaments that connect bones at the major joints": "",
  "Smooth muscle lines the walls of hollow visceral organs (stomach, intestines, blood vessels, bladder, uterus) and is involuntary, meaning it contracts without conscious control to move substances through these organs.": "",
  "Tendons are composed of:": "",
  "Cartilage": "",
  "Dense regular connective tissue": "",
  "Loose connective tissue": "",
  "Tendons are made of dense regular connective tissue, which has parallel bundles of collagen fibers providing great tensile strength in one direction, ideal for attaching muscles to bones.": "",
  "Nervous tissue is composed of:": "",
  "Only neurons": "",
  "Neurons and neuroglia (glial cells)": "",
  "Only glial cells": "",
  "Red blood cells and platelets": "",
  "Nervous tissue contains two main cell types: neurons, which generate and transmit electrical impulses, and neuroglia (glial cells), which support, insulate, and protect the neurons.": "",
  "Simple squamous epithelium is found in the:": "",
  "Tendons and ligaments": "",
  "Alveoli of the lungs and lining of blood vessels": "",
  "Outer surface of the skin": "",
  "Brain and spinal cord": "",
  "Simple squamous epithelium consists of a single layer of thin, flat cells that allow rapid diffusion and filtration, making it ideal for the alveoli (gas exchange) and blood vessel linings (endothelium).": "",
  "Which muscle type features intercalated discs?": "",
  "Cardiac muscle": "",
  "All muscle types": "",
  "Smooth muscle": "",
  "Skeletal muscle": "",
  "Intercalated discs are specialized cell junctions unique to cardiac muscle that contain gap junctions and desmosomes, allowing electrical signals to pass rapidly between cells so the heart contracts as a coordinated unit.": "",
  "What is histology?": "",
  "The microscopic study of tissues, their structure, and their functions": "",
  "The study of genes and heredity": "",
  "The study of organs and organ systems": "",
  "The study of whole-body anatomy": "",
  "Histology (from histo- meaning tissue and -logy meaning study of) is the branch of anatomy that examines the microscopic structure of tissues to understand how their cellular organization relates to their function.": "",
  "What is epithelial tissue?": "",
  "Tissue that provides structural support through a mineralized matrix": "",
  "Tissue that transmits electrical impulses": "",
  "Tissue that contracts to produce movement": "",
  "Tissue that covers body surfaces, lines body cavities, and forms glands for secretion": "",
  "Epithelial tissue is a sheet of tightly packed cells that covers external body surfaces (skin), lines internal cavities and organs, and forms glands (both endocrine and exocrine) that secrete various substances.": "",
  "What does 'striated' mean when describing muscle tissue?": "",
  "Lacking any nucleus": "",
  "Having multiple layers of cells stacked on a basement membrane": "",
  "Having a smooth, uniform appearance under the microscope": "",
  "Having visible alternating light and dark cross-stripes (bands) from organized sarcomeres": "",
  "Striated means having visible cross-stripes or bands when viewed under a microscope, which result from the highly organized arrangement of actin and myosin filaments into repeating units called sarcomeres in skeletal and cardiac muscle.": "",
  "What is the extracellular matrix?": "",
  "The internal fluid compartment within cells that houses metabolic enzymes and dissolved ions": "",
  "The membrane-bound organelles inside a cell that carry out specialized metabolic functions": "",
  "The phospholipid bilayer plasma membrane that forms the outer boundary of each living cell": "",
  "The non-living material found between cells, composed of ground substance and protein fibers": "",
  "The extracellular matrix (ECM) is the material produced by cells that fills the space between them, consisting of ground substance (water, proteins, polysaccharides) and protein fibers (collagen, elastic, reticular). It is especially prominent in connective tissues.": "",
  "What is adipose tissue?": "",
  "A type of nervous tissue found in the brain": "",
  "A type of epithelial tissue that lines the stomach": "",
  "A type of muscle tissue that produces voluntary movement": "",
  "A type of connective tissue specialized for fat storage, insulation, and cushioning": "",
  "Adipose tissue is a specialized type of loose connective tissue composed of adipocytes (fat cells) that store triglycerides for energy, provide thermal insulation, and cushion and protect organs.": "",
  "What does 'neuroglia' mean?": "",
  "The cells that produce blood in bone marrow": "",
  "The connective tissue wrapping around muscles": "",
  "The supportive cells of nervous tissue that protect, insulate, and nourish neurons": "",
  "The signal-carrying cells of the nervous system": "",
  "Neuroglia (glial cells) are the non-neuronal cells of the nervous system that provide support, protection, insulation (myelination), and nutrition to neurons. They outnumber neurons and include astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, microglia, and Schwann cells.": "",
  "What is osseous tissue?": "",
  "The lining tissue of the respiratory tract": "",
  "Soft tissue found in the brain": "",
  "Muscle tissue that lines the walls of blood vessels": "",
  "Bone tissue, a type of connective tissue with a hard, calcified extracellular matrix": "",
  "Osseous (bone) tissue is a connective tissue characterized by osteocytes (bone cells) embedded in a hard, mineralized extracellular matrix rich in calcium phosphate, providing structural support and protection for the body.": "",
  "What is glandular epithelium?": "",
  "Connective tissue that produces blood cells": "",
  "Epithelial tissue specialized to form glands that produce and secrete substances such as hormones, enzymes, or mucus": "",
  "Muscle tissue found in the heart wall": "",
  "Nervous tissue that lines the spinal cord": "",
  "Glandular epithelium consists of epithelial cells specialized for secretion, forming endocrine glands (which release hormones into the blood) and exocrine glands (which release products through ducts, such as sweat, saliva, and digestive enzymes).": "",
  "What does 'stratified' mean when describing epithelial tissue?": "",
  "Having multiple layers of cells stacked on top of each other": "",
  "Having cells that are all the same height": "",
  "Having a single layer of cells": "",
  "Lacking a basement membrane": "",
  "Stratified epithelium has two or more layers of cells, which provides increased protection against abrasion and mechanical stress. Stratified squamous epithelium, found in the skin and mouth, is the most common stratified type.": "",
  "What is cartilage?": "",
  "A type of connective tissue with a firm but flexible extracellular matrix that provides support and reduces friction at joints": "",
  "A type of nervous tissue found in the peripheral nerves": "",
  "A type of muscle tissue that is involuntary and non-striated": "",
  "A type of epithelial tissue that lines the lungs": "",
  "Cartilage is a connective tissue composed of chondrocytes embedded in a firm but flexible matrix of collagen and proteoglycans. It provides structural support, reduces friction at joints, and forms the framework for structures like the ear and nose.": "",
  "A medical student is examining a tissue slide and observes a single layer of flat cells lining a structure. The professor explains this tissue allows rapid diffusion. The student is most likely viewing a slide of:": "",
  "Simple squamous epithelium from an alveolus or blood vessel": "",
  "Stratified squamous epithelium from the skin": "",
  "Smooth muscle from the intestinal wall": "",
  "Dense regular connective tissue from a tendon": "",
  "A single layer (simple) of flat (squamous) cells that permits rapid diffusion is characteristic of simple squamous epithelium, found in the alveoli of the lungs (for gas exchange) and the endothelium lining blood vessels.": "",
  "During a lab dissection, a student notices that the tissue connecting a muscle to a bone is very tough and has a silvery-white appearance with parallel fibers. This tissue is most likely:": "",
  "Simple columnar epithelium": "",
  "Adipose tissue": "",
  "Dense regular connective tissue (a tendon)": "",
  "Tendons are made of dense regular connective tissue, which has tightly packed parallel collagen fibers that give it a silvery-white appearance and tremendous tensile strength for anchoring muscles to bones.": "",
  "A patient presents with a skin abrasion on the palm of her hand that has worn through several layers of cells. The damaged tissue is most likely:": "",
  "Cardiac muscle tissue": "",
  "Simple squamous epithelium": "",
  "Stratified squamous epithelium": "",
  "The skin (especially on areas subject to friction like the palms) is lined with stratified squamous epithelium, which has multiple layers of cells specifically adapted to resist abrasion and protect deeper tissues.": "",
  "A pathologist examining a biopsy of heart tissue under the microscope observes striated cells with centrally placed nuclei connected by dark-staining junctions. These dark junctions are:": "",
  "Tendons connecting muscle to bone": "",
  "Basement membranes of epithelial tissue": "",
  "Neuromuscular junctions": "",
  "Intercalated discs unique to cardiac muscle": "",
  "Intercalated discs are specialized cell junctions found only in cardiac muscle tissue. They contain gap junctions (for rapid electrical signal transmission) and desmosomes (for mechanical strength), allowing the heart to contract as a synchronized unit.": "",
  "A nurse is explaining to a patient that blood tests can reveal many health conditions because blood travels through every organ. In histological terms, blood is classified as a connective tissue because:": "",
  "It covers body surfaces like epithelial tissue": "",
  "It transmits electrical signals like nervous tissue": "",
  "It consists of cells (RBCs, WBCs, platelets) dispersed in a liquid extracellular matrix called plasma": "",
  "It contracts to pump itself through vessels": "",
  "Blood is classified as a connective tissue because, like all connective tissues, it has cells dispersed within an extracellular matrix. In blood's case, the matrix is a liquid (plasma) rather than a solid or gel-like substance.": "",
  "A medical student is studying a slide of intestinal wall and observes a layer of muscle tissue with no visible striations that appears to contract slowly and rhythmically. This tissue is most likely:": "",
  "Dense irregular connective tissue": "",
  "Smooth muscle is found in the walls of hollow organs like the intestines, lacks striations (hence the name 'smooth'), and contracts involuntarily to move food through the digestive tract via peristalsis.": "",
  "A radiologist reviewing a knee MRI identifies damage to the flexible, firm tissue cushioning the ends of the femur and tibia. A student asks what type of tissue this is. The correct answer is:": "",
  "Osseous (bone) tissue": "",
  "Cartilage (hyaline cartilage)": "",
  "Hyaline cartilage covers the ends of bones at synovial joints (articular cartilage), providing a smooth, low-friction surface and acting as a shock absorber. Damage to this cartilage is a common finding in joint injuries and osteoarthritis.": "",
  "A patient recovering from surgery has a wound that is healing with scar tissue. A medical student explains that scar tissue is primarily composed of:": "",
  "Nervous tissue regenerating the original nerve pathways": "",
  "New epithelial cells replacing the damaged area": "",
  "New muscle tissue replacing the damaged area": "",
  "Dense irregular connective tissue rich in collagen fibers": "",
  "Scar tissue (fibrosis) forms from dense irregular connective tissue produced by fibroblasts during wound healing. The collagen fibers are deposited in a random pattern, making the scar strong but less flexible than the original tissue.": "",
  "A physiology professor shows students a microscope slide containing cells with long, cylindrical shapes, multiple nuclei per cell, and visible striations. A student correctly identifies this as:": "",
  "Smooth muscle tissue": "",
  "Skeletal muscle tissue": "",
  "Skeletal muscle fibers are long, cylindrical, multinucleated cells with prominent striations. These features distinguish them from cardiac muscle (which has single central nuclei and intercalated discs) and smooth muscle (which lacks striations and has single nuclei).": "",
  "A clinical instructor asks a nursing student why obese patients may have difficulty regulating body temperature. The student correctly explains that excessive adipose tissue can impair heat dissipation because:": "",
  "Adipose tissue produces sweat that cools the body too quickly": "",
  "Adipose tissue generates too much heat through contraction": "",
  "Adipose tissue is a connective tissue that acts as an insulating layer, making it harder for heat to escape from the body": "",
  "Adipose tissue transmits nerve signals that raise the thermostat": "",
  "Adipose (fat) tissue serves as thermal insulation because it conducts heat poorly. While this insulation is beneficial in cold environments, excessive adipose tissue can trap heat and impair the body's ability to dissipate heat during exercise or in hot conditions.": ""
}